    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1976-12-01T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1976-12-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="263"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d263">
                <head>263. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d263fn1"
                        >Source: National Archives, RG 59, Central Foreign Policy Files,
                        P820118–1945. Secret; Sensitive; Nodis.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d263fn2">Colombian Foreign Minister Lievano
                        presented his views to <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> and
                            <persName corresp="#p_RWD1">Rogers</persName> concerning incorporating
                        human rights issues into <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss>–Latin American
                        relations.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Mexico City</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1976-12-01">December 1,
                        1976</date>
                </dateline>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS:</head>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> Side</item>
                    <item>The Secretary</item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_RWD1">William Rogers</persName>, Under Secretary
                        for Economic Affairs</item>
                    <item>Colombia Side</item>
                    <item>Foreign Minister Indalecio Lievano Aguirre</item>
                </list>
                <p>The Secretary met over lunch with Foreign Minister Lievano. Lievano stressed
                    human rights and touched on Panama and economic relations as well.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="underline">Human Rights</hi>: This issue was at the top of Lievano’s
                    agenda. His suggestion was blunt: do not hang <gloss target="#t_US1"
                        >U.S.</gloss> policy in the hemisphere around the human rights issue. To
                    make human rights performance the test of our relationship with the nations of
                    the Americas would chill our ties with a goodly number who happen not to share
                    our own democratic preferences just now, would create no end of difficulties for
                    the few other democracies, and would probably not do much for human rights.</p>
                <p>[Omitted here is material unrelated to human rights policy.]</p>
            </div>
